# Design System and Styling

## Color Application

- Apply design system colors using Tailwind classes instead of modifying global.css
- Use Tailwind utility classes instead of CSS variables directly

## Typography

- Use custom typography classes from global.css for text styling
  - Examples: `body-lg-bold`, `body-lg-medium`, `body-sm-light`
- Use custom classes instead of directly specifying font, size, or line-height
- Maintain color and Tailwind naming conventions

## Tailwind CSS v4 Usage

- Use Tailwind utility classes instead of CSS variables directly
- Project uses Tailwind CSS v4, so follow the latest syntax

# Project Management

## Memory Management

- Use memory.md file to manage Figma MCP call steps
- Prevent hallucinations and reuse context across chats
- Automatically manage pipeline step states and share across chat sessions

## Workflow

- Store each step of Figma MCP calls in memory.md
- Use memory.md throughout the project to manage pipeline step states
- Automatically share context across chat sessions

# Development Guidelines

## Code Generation Considerations

- Maintain design system consistency
- Prioritize Tailwind classes
- Utilize custom typography classes
- Manage context through memory system

## File Structure

- Maintain existing directory structure
- Follow structure under apps/web/src/shared/ui/common
- Follow component naming and structure patterns

# FSD (Feature-Sliced Design) Structure

- The project follows the FSD (Feature-Sliced Design) structure.
- Main folder roles:
  - features: Independent business feature units (e.g., auth, match, record, etc.)
  - entities: Core domain models and their subfolders such as UI, API, model, etc.
  - shared: Utilities, components, and styles commonly used across features
  - widgets: UI blocks that combine multiple entities/features (e.g., header, navigation, etc.)
- Within each folder, clearly separate subfolders by role, such as ui, model, api, lib, etc.
- When adding new features or components, place them according to the FSD structure and their intended role.

